 that sums up the difference from the old game and the new game.  And, yes, I really think if you start playing now you are essentially playing a different game.  <br><br>On CT, before EC was the constant 24/7 trade zone, there was a travelling bazaar each weekend.  Nobody really did any trading except at these bazaars, so everybody went on trade day.  The first time they held it in Butcherblock, so many people were trying to ride the boat at once, the boat crashed.  Every time they reset it, another 50 would jump on and crash it again.  About half the current server population was trapped, until the &quot;uber guilds&quot; called out their &quot;high level&quot; wizards and druids to start porting people back to the mainland.  One zone crashing brought the entire server to panic.  <br><br>If the boats from FP to BB went down for a few hours today, I wonder if more than a handful of people would even notice. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/ublearchie.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Blearchie</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Board Benefactor</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/7/02 3:38:08 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=782.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~jim_howard/sig.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: EQ Evolution</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Overcrowding was a bitvh, but that was the only real problem. And undercrowding is worse <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br><br>A very good point.<br><br>At release up until I &quot;retired&quot; from EQ (about the time RoK was released), I played a ranger. I was lucky enough to meet up with a good mix of friends that made a perfect balanced group and loved to crawl the caves. Paw before it was revamped(had to get that uber snakeskin stuff), upper guk, cazic (rubicite!), places that we were often the only group in the zone.<br><br>We discovered low guk one evening while exploring upper and all of a sudden LOADING PLEASE WAIT... wtf? a /w showed 12 people in the zone including the 6 of us. We ended up having to team up to make it to the tower area <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  It became our new home.<br><br>Slowly, as more folks discovered the zone you could start finding 30 and 40 folks in the zone. That's a fairly comfortable number for there. <br><br>Eventually it got too crowded. By time I quit EQ, you could zone in and find 100+ in low guk and walk to the ghoul lord without ivu. It was simply too crowded to be fun anymore.<br><br>Like most folks out there, I have my little twinks I like to play. Of course there are certain caves I love and low guk is one of them. Now when you zone in, you tend to find a cave full of high level campers and few groups looking to grind. Most folks in the 40-50 range seem to prefer the safety of dreadlands while low guk is underused. As a die hard dungeon crawler, it's rough. <p>Blearchie Pooh<BR>Phantasmist of CoFE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/usanterre.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Santerre</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Board Veteran</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/7/02 7:49:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=782.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: EQ Evolution</span><hr size=1> I was kind of lucky.  I started in July '99.  By that time, a couple guilds on Sol Ro had their first group of twinks working.  I ended up grouping pretty regularly with Avaran the clerc (Callie) and Jorash the paladin (he played an ogre warrior, forgot the name, its been a while) from Paradigm.  As I look back now, they were very twinked (Dragon and Guk loot)... and I think they were somewhat amused by the fact that I didn't realize it or care.  Anyways, in the bowels of Cazic-Thule, Unrest, and Mistmoore they taught me how to play the game - how to assist, when to cast my damage shield, when the druid needs to backup heal so he doesn't waste the clerics mana, what happens when the druid forgets to snare (heh!), what I can and cannot cast on mezzed mobs, what you want to make hotkeys for, how to manage aggro, root park - a million other things that I and other good players take for granted.<br><br>So I guess I lament the loss of these places... but it is true - there's more content in the game over 50 than under 50, and VI put in effective ways to get there, and I'd rather play my main in ToV than a twink in LGuk. <p><BR><br><B><I><img src="http://www.druidmail.com/santerre2.gif">Santerre.</I></B></p><i></i></td></tr></table><table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showMessage?topicID=778.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showMessage?topicID=764.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=782.topic&index=20><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/grunge/addReply.jpg border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.emailToFriend?topicID=782.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0 alt="Email This To a Friend"> Email This To a Friend</a><br> <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.threadControl?topicID=782.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/grunge/deleteThread.